{"title":"End-to-End Transformer Based Model for Image Captioning","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Most image captioning systems rely on pre-trained object detectors (e.g., Faster R-CNN) to extract region features, creating a two-stage pipeline that is computationally heavy and not end-to-end; LSTM decoders further limit training efficiency and expressiveness.","method":"PureT is a fully Transformer-based, one-stage captioner trained end-to-end. It uses Swin Transformer to extract grid-level visual features and computes a global image feature via mean pooling. A refining encoder alternates windowed and shifted-window self-attention (W-MSA/SW-MSA) to capture intra-image relations; the global feature is injected as an extra token into keys/values within each window and is also refined by querying all grid tokens, enabling mutual guidance between local and global context. A standard Transformer decoder then generates captions from the refined grid and global features, yielding state-of-the-art results on MSCOCO."},{"problem":"In Transformer-based captioning, vision–language interaction typically occurs only at cross-attention, leaving the decoder without global visual context early in processing, which weakens reasoning over the image.","method":"PureT introduces a pre-fusion module in every decoder block that concatenates the refined global visual feature with previously generated word embeddings before masked self-attention, providing an early inter-modal interaction. This is followed by language masked self-attention and then cross-attention over the refined grid features. Ablation studies show the pre-fusion consistently improves all metrics compared to variants without it."},{"problem":"The best choice of visual backbone for Transformer decoders in captioning—and how backbone–decoder combinations interact—has been unclear (region vs. grid features; CNN vs. ViT-family).","method":"The paper systematically compares backbones (Faster R-CNN with ResNet/ResNeXt region features, ViT grid features, and Swin Transformer grid features) across multiple decoders (M2 Transformer, X-Transformer, standard Transformer, and PureT). Results show Swin Transformer grid features deliver the largest, most consistent gains—especially with decoders using standard MSA—while CNN-based region features pair better with LSTM or Transformer variants using non-standard attention. These findings guide backbone selection and motivate PureT’s Swin-based, standard-MSA design."}]}
